A desktop personal computer. Generally depicted as a black or gray monitor with a dark or blue screen.Like💻 Laptop Computer, used for various content concerning computer technology, work, and activity. Acomputerprinter, as at a home office. Generally depicted as a grayish device with a power button and paper loaded in its tray, sometimes printing out a document. A keyboard, as used to type on acomputer. Generally depicted as a gray device with white or black keys. Used for various content concerning computers, typing, and writing.Apple’s design resembles the company’sMagic Keyboard. Microsoft's design is blue.Not to be confused with🎹 Musical Keyboard.

A mouse, as used to control a cursor on acomputer. A trackball, as rotated to control a cursor on a computer. An alternative or supplement to acomputer mouseor touchpad. Aminidisc, depicted as a small, silver or goldoptical dischoused in a square cartridge, its shutter positioned to the right.Discontinuedas an audio and data storage format in 2013 due to the success of CD and MP3 technology, though the emoji is commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, and related film and music content, especially albums.Samsung’s designpreviously featureda silver disc labeledMD, forminidisc.Early designsfrom au by KDDI showed an angled💾 Floppy Disk, perhaps as being inserted or ejected into a computer drive.See also💿 Optical Discand📀 DVD.

A silveroptical disc, as a CD orDVD, used to play music or movies before the rise of streaming technology. Commonly used to represent CDs, DVDs, Blu-rays, and related film and music content, especially albums.See also💽 Computer Diskand📀 DVD.

Adigital versatile disc(DVD), a type ofoptical discused to play movies before the rise of streaming technology. Anabacus, an ancient tool used to count and calculate by moving beads. The back of an envelope, as used to send a letter or card in the mail (post). Generally depicted in white, though Google’s design is yellow. Used for various content concerning mail and messages, includingemail.Samsung’s designpreviously featureda red, wax seal imprinted with the initial M.

Depicted as the back of an envelope imprinted with a capital letter E (forelectronic) or @ (at) sign.Commonly used as an icon before an email address.The envelope is generally white (except for Google’s yellow design) and the E or @, blue. Apple and Google’s designs feature the letter E, Microsoft and Samsung’s the @ sign.

The back of an envelope, shown coming into an inbox or arriving with motion lines.Commonly used as an icon for anemailaddress. Microsoft and Facebook’s designs feature a yellow envelope angled forward and trailed by three, blue lines, indicating sending.Apple’s designpreviously featuredthree red motion lines,Microsoft’sa right arrow.

The back ofenvelopewith adown arrowon top. Generally depicted in white (except for Google’s yellow design) with a red or blue arrow.Commonly used an icon before anemailaddress. May also represent downloading, direct messages, or mail (post) more generally. Its original intent may have been to indicate sealing and delivering a letter in an envelope.Microsoft’s designpreviously resembledanincoming envelope.Early designs from Applefeatured a right arrow with the envelope oriented lengthwise. A paper tray with anup arrowon top, as a symbol for anemailoutbox. An open, curbside mailbox (letterbox,postbox) with its signal flag raised and a letter in its open slot. A curbside mailbox (letterbox,postbox) with its signal flag lowered and its slot empty. A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with aletterin its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled afterpublic postboxes in Japan. A ballot box, as used to cast votes in an election. Depicted as a box, generally blue or gray, with a slot on top through which a paper ballot is being inserted. A classic yellow pencil. Depicted as a graphite pencil, like a U.S. #2 or European HB, with a sharpened tip and pink eraser. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. The silvernibof a fountain pen, which distributes ink onto a writing surface. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. A black fountain pen with a silvernib, as used for signing important documents. Often depicted with gold hardware. Positioned at a 45° angle with its tip at the lower left. A blue or black ballpoint pen, as used for everyday writing. Depicted with its cap removed onto its end or as retractable pen. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning writing (e.g., creative, professional) as well as signing (deals, laws, in sports).Google's designpreviously featureda brown-colored pen. A thin, artist's paintbrush, as used to paint apicture. Often depicted with reddish paint on its pointed bristles. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left.Commonly used for various content concerning the art of painting or fine art more generally. Often paired with🎨Artist Palette.

A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling aCrayola crayon. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. A white piece of paper with text written on it by a yellowpencil, positioned over the sheet, tip down, at a 45° angle. The round pegs in the square holes…Not to be confused with📄 Page Facing Upor other emojis featuring sheets of paper.

A tabbed folder, as used to file papers in acabinetor as an icon for a file on acomputer. A slightly open tabbed folder, as used to file papers in acabinetor as an icon for an opened folder when usingacomputer. A single date on a calendar. A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page on a two-ringed, daily desk calendar, as flipped or torn off to change the date. A spiral-bound, flip-style notepad or notebook of lined paper, as used for everyday note-taking. A card index, as aRolodex, once used to organize and access cards containing the information of personal or business contacts. A graph showing a red (or sometimes green) trend line increasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. A graph showing a colored trend line, often blue, decreasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. A bar graph generally showing three different-colored, vertical rectangles at various heights, as compares values across a category. A white piece of paper secured by a silver clip on a brown clipboard, as used as a writing surface when standing. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, especially in sports.Many platforms indicate text with dark lines. WhatsApp’s design shows lined paper. Facebook’s features the easter egg of a table with first names and numbers, perhaps as birthdates:Matt 3/28Louie 4/30Alexa 6/17Brian 8/06Apple’s design also features an easter egg, addressedDear Katieand signedTake carefromJohn Appleseedwith the text of its 1997–2002Crazy Ones/Think Differentad campaign:Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.

A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. A pushpin, as used to indicate a location on amap. A silver paper clip, as used to hold together sheets of paper—or remove a SIM card from amobile phone. Shown positioned at various angles.Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies. A ruler, as used to draw straight lines and measure distances. A pair of scissors, as used to cut paper orhair. Generally shown open, blades down, with red handles. A black or gray box with a label holder, containingcard index dividerswith multicolored tabs, as used to organize and store files.Apple and Facebook’s designs include a lid.Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work.Microsoft’s designpreviously resembleda shoebox.

An unlockedpadlock, as used to secure a latch or chain,oras an icon for anon-secure connectionoropen accessonline. A locked (closed)padlockwith a fountain pen ornibpositioned at various angles in front of it.Vendors implement the same design as their🔒 Lockedand the same or similar design as their🖋️ Fountain Penor✒️ Black Nib.May represent digital certificates inpublic-key technology. An old-fashioned key, as opens an antique chest or wardrobe. A pointed knife with a steel blade, as used for thrusting in close combat. A squirt gun (water pistol), as used tospray waterfor fun.On major platforms, depicted as a green or orange toy gun with an orange tip and barrel pointed left.Google, Microsoft, and Facebook’s designs include mounted reservoirs.Originally depicted as a classic handgun, as a revolver or other pistol. A shield, as blocks swords in close combat. A balance scale, as historically used to measure weight. A symbol of justice, as held byLady Justice, and of thezodiac signofLibra, the Scales. A probingcane,used by some people who are blind or visually impaired. Differs from asupport cane, and is sometimesreferred toas awhite cane. See also👩‍🦯 Woman With Probing Caneand👨‍🦯 Man With Probing Cane.White Canewas approved as part ofUnicode 12.0in 2019

Two links of a silverchain, positioned at a 45° angle. Used as an icon for ahyperlinkon computers and the internet. May also be used for metaphorical connections.Not to be confused with⛓️Chains,📎 Paperclip,🖇️ Linked Paperclips, or🧷 Safety Pin.

Two parallel lengths of silver chain. Occasionally used as an icon before ahyperlinkor for metaphorical connections or chains, e.g., slangoff the chains.Samsung’s designpreviously featuredstylized, white chains in a blue square, as a sign or icon forsnow chainsfor winter driving.Not to be confused with🔗 Link,📎 Paperclip,🖇️ Linked Paperclips, or🧷 Safety Pin.

A horseshoe magnet, as used to pick upiron.Depicted at various angles in red with silver-tipped poles.Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative magnetism and attraction. An apparatus for distilling, as used in medievalalchemy. Generally depicted as a round flask with a neck angled down to the right. The double helix ofDNA, the genetic blueprint for life. Amicroscope, as used in science laboratories to magnify small objects, such ascellsorinsects. A telescope, as used to gaze atstarsandplanetsin the night sky. A dish antenna, as used to send or receive information to or from a communicationsatellite—or👽 Extraterrestrial Life. A medical syringe, as used to administer a shot or drawblood. A couch (sofa) with a floor lamp on the right, as in theliving room of ahouse. Color and style of the couch and lamp vary widely by platform.Used for various content concerning furniture and housing as well as resting and lounging.

A silver shower head, streaming water to the left. Pressure level varies across platforms.🧼Soapnot provided.Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and water. Shower heads are also featured in🛁Bathtuband🛀Person Taking a Bath.

A bottle of lotion for the skin, such as moisturizer or sunscreen (sunblock). A silver safety pin or clip, as used to fasten fabric. Generally shown clasped at a 45° angle, with its spring at the lower left.May be used for various content concerning arts, crafts, and sewing. Not to be confused with📎Paperclip.
